05021nam a22009135i 9780813594798DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135947987 a10.36019/97808135947982doi  a(DE-B1597)526380  a(OCoLC)1030304700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aEDU0000002bisacsh1 aBrooms, Derrick R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aEmpowering Men of Color on Campus :bBuilding Student Community in Higher Education /cDerrick R. Brooms, Matthew Smith, Jelisa Clark. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Campus00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Men Of Color In Higher Education -- t2. Race, Resilience, And Naming One's Own Reality In The Transition To College -- t3. Building Community From Cultural Wealth -- t4. Engaging And Empowering Black And Latino Men Through Leadership -- t5. (Re)Imagining And (Re)Writing The Narrative -- t6. Supporting Men Of Color'S Success Efforts -- tAppendix A: Participants In The Study -- tAppendix B: Data Analysis, Validation, And Conclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile recruitment efforts toward men of color have increased at many colleges and universities, their retention and graduation rates still lag behind those of their white peers. Men of color, particularly black and Latino men, face a number of unique challenges in their educational careers that often impact their presence on campus and inhibit their collegiate success. Empowering Men of Color on Campus examines how men of color negotiate college through their engagement in Brothers for United Success (B4US), an institutionally-based male-centered program at a Hispanic Serving Institution. Derrick R. Brooms, Jelisa Clark, and Matthew Smith introduce the concept of educational agency, which is harbored in cultural wealth and demonstrates how ongoing B4US engagement empowers the men's efforts and abilities to persist in college. They found that the cultural wealth(s) of the community enhanced the students' educational agency, which bolstered their academic aspirations, academic and social engagement, and personal development. The authors demonstrate how educational agency and cultural wealth can be developed and refined given salient and meaningful immersions, experiences, engagements, and communal connections.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 4aAfrican American. 4aB4US. 4aBrothers for United Success. 4aLatino. 4aagency. 4ablack. 4abrothers united success. 4acollege. 4aculture. 4aeducation. 4ahigher education. 4amen of color. 4amen. 4arace. 4auniversity. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aClark, Jelisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.1 aSmith, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066330308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065742508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018z978311066608340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813594798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813594798.jpg  a978-3-11-065742-5  RUP eBook-Package 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066330-3  RUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-066608-3  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alle